HEADWORD: Archipelago
<hw>Ar`chi*pel"a*go</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>-goes</plw> or <plw>-gos</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[It.
<ets>arcipelago</ets>, properly, chief sea; Gr. pref <?/ + <?/ sea,
perh. akin to <?/ blow, and expressing the beating of the waves. See
<er>Plague</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The Grecian Archipelago, or ⟦AE⟧gean Sea, separating
Greece from Asia Minor. It is studded with a vast number of small
islands.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence: Any sea or broad sheet of water interspersed
with many islands or with a group of islands.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 79 --></p>

